            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36.39"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">39</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>April 13, 1972</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear John,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p><hi rend="caps">OF COURSE</hi> you haven't offended me! I like your joking; it's a sign of affection, and anyway, what could you ever do to offend me when I love you so much? I'm terribly sorry you have to have trouble with the old respiration again, but I'm holding the best of good wishes and thoughts for you, and I know you"ll be better. I hate for you to be ill; you must do whatever they say so you'll bounce back and feel ready for spring again. You always did belong to spring.</p>
                
                <p>I am writing Myrtle too, and I'll give her the details of news. I didn't mean to be so long writing you, but we are in a terrible crisis at the University about money, and all anyone has done for the past month is attend committee, department, faculty, special, and interminable meetings to try to find ways to save money without firing faculty and cutting out courses. Two entire departments may be scrapped, and when that is even suggested the situation is crucial. It's unpleasant because people are frightened and fear doesn't bring out the best in people sometimes. I think it may be better soon, but we are putting in days you wouldn't believe. We (Bower and I) got out of a meeting at 6:40 last ngiht and poor Bower had to teach a seminar at 7--he didn't even have time for dinner.</p>
                
                <p>I do have some things to tell you. All sorts of classes are using Black Elk--one I just learned about in Junior High! People are "discovering" you right and left, and I see your books in every store. Also I'm getting at the final alterations on the Biography before it goes to the second reader. And today I had a letter from a commercial publisher about a simplified version next year--all tentative, but I thought you'd be interested. Say the name Neihardt now, and eyes light up!!!</p> 
                
                <p>So get well fast, and feel our love from out here where the roses are almost in bloom. I'm thinking about you. Much love from Bower, and me.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Lucile</signed> 
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
